[03:38] <pmichaud> sorear: at one time, lexpads weren't so intimately tied to subs -- i.e., one could get a new pad without having to invoke another sub to do it
[03:38] <pmichaud> that got torn out a few years ago, and several of us at the time wondered if that was perhaps a mistake
[03:39] <tcurtis> Can lexicals be removed from a lexpad after they've been added?
[03:39] <sorear> Lexicals can't be added to a lexpad
[03:39] <pmichaud> lexpads in parrot are (currently) intimately tied to sub contexts
[03:39] <sorear> .lex should be treated as an attribute of the sub
[03:39] <sorear> its location has no effect
[03:39] <pmichaud> i.e., the keys of the lexpad are fixed at compile-time by the .lex declarations within the sub
[03:40] <tcurtis> Ah.
[03:40] <pmichaud> (there are special directives to change this, but that's Parrot's default)
[03:40] <pmichaud> not only that, but the .lex declarations tie the lexpad entry to a specific pmc register in the context
[03:41] <pmichaud> the "values" in a lexpad aren't the pmc registers, but rather the index of the pmc register in the context
[03:41] <pmichaud> (keys are lexical names, values are index into the pmc register frame)
[03:42] <pmichaud> so, even if you get hold of the current lexpad hash, you can't add new entries to the lexpad
[03:42] <pmichaud> I suspect you could delete entries from it, though.
[03:43] <pmichaud> (it wouldn't have any effect other than to make the lexical name disappear from view.)
[03:44] <pmichaud> actually, come to think of it, I doubt the delete_keyed vtable is even defined for Parrot LexPads
[03:44] <pmichaud> so no deletion :-)
